{ix} Preface
{ix} 前言
This book is a brief introduction to the art of making arguments. It sticks to the bare essentials. I have found that students and writers often need just such a list of reminders and rules, not lengthy introductory explanations. This book is therefore organized around specific rules, illustrated and explained soundly but above all briefly. It is not a textbook but a rule book.
本书是对论证艺术的简要介绍，只聚焦于最基本的要素。我发现，学生和写作者往往需要的正是这样一份提醒和规则清单，而非冗长的入门讲解。因此，本书围绕具体的规则展开，辅以图解和清晰的解释，但最重要的是简洁明了。它不是一本教科书，而是一本规则手册。
Instructors too, I have found, often wish to assign such a rulebook, a treatment that students can consult and understand on their own and that therefore does not claim too much class time. Here again, it is important to be brief—the point is to help students get on with their actual arguments—but the rules must be stated with enough substance that an instructor can simply refer a student to Rule 6 or Rule 16 rather than give an entire explanation each time it is needed. Brief but self-sufficient—that is the fine line I have tried to follow.
我发现，教师们也常常希望布置这样一份规则手册，方便学生自行查阅和理解，从而节省课堂时间。同样，简洁至关重要——目的是帮助学生专注于实际论证——但规则的表述必须足够详尽，以便教师只需引导学生查阅规则6或规则16，而无需每次都进行完整解释。简洁而又自洽——这正是我一直努力遵循的原则。
This rulebook also can be used in a course that gives critical attention to arguments. It will need to be supplemented with exercises and more examples, but many texts are already available that consist largely or wholly of such exercises and examples. Those texts, however, also need to be supplemented—with what this rulebook offers: simple rules for putting good arguments together. We do not want our students to come out of critical thinking courses knowing only how to shoot down (or just at ) selected fallacies. Critical thinking can be practiced in a far more constructive spirit. This book is one attempt to suggest how.
这本规则手册也适用于注重批判性论证的课程。虽然需要辅以练习和更多示例，但市面上已有许多教材主要或完全由此类练习和示例构成。然而，这些教材也需要补充——而这本规则手册正是提供了这样的补充：构建有效论证的简明规则。我们不希望学生从批判性思维课程毕业后，仅仅知道如何驳斥（或仅仅反驳）某些特定的谬误。批判性思维的实践可以更加注重建设性。本书正是对此的一种尝试。
#↩
{x} Note to the Fifth Edition
{x} 第五版注释
Rulebook continues to find a wide use in a variety of schools, from high school to law school, and in other settings too. The world continues to change as well. In this fifth edition there are several corresponding changes. Most notably, I have added a new final chapter, “Public Debates,” which repositions a few of the old rules but mostly adds new ones. The state of our public debate at the moment is pretty sorry, and while this surely has many causes, a better understanding of the etiquette and the ethics of good public debate should help. Six short rules—but what a difference they might make!
《规则手册》在各类院校，从高中到法学院，以及其他场合，都得到了广泛应用。世界也在不断变化。第五版也随之做出了一些相应的改动。最显著的是，我新增了最后一章“公开辩论”，其中调整了一些旧规则，但主要新增了一些规则。目前，我们的公开辩论状况令人堪忧，这当然有很多原因，但更好地理解良好公开辩论的礼仪和伦理规范应该会有所帮助。六条简短的规则——但它们或许能带来巨大的改变！
Smaller changes include a number of updated examples, drawing on a wider and more contemporary range of sources. Goodbye Einstein, hello Beyoncé. This edition is a little fresher, a little tighter, a bit more humorous. Some of the rules have acquired punchy subtitles. This is no time to be timid about the need for good arguments and better ways of arguing, either, so you may find this new edition somewhat edgier as well.
一些细微的改动包括更新了部分示例，这些示例取材更广泛、更现代。告别爱因斯坦，迎接碧昂丝。这一版更加清新、精炼、幽默。部分规则还配上了醒目的副标题。如今，我们更不应畏惧提出有力的论证和改进论证方式，因此，您或许也会觉得新版更具锋芒。
For instructors and students who may be interested, I am happy to add that a companion textbook to A Rulebook for Arguments is now available. David Morrow and I have written it ourselves: A Workbook for Arguments. Workbook includes the entire Rulebook, but between each section of this brief guide, Workbook interpolates further explanations and extensive examples and exercises, with a thorough selection of sample answers as well. Many thanks to Professor Morrow for convincing me and Hackett Publishing Company of the need for and appeal of such a textbook, and then doing the lion’s share of the work on it, carrying it now through two editions (first edition 2013; second edition 2016). David’s insights and suggestions have helped shape this new edition of Rulebook as well.
对于可能感兴趣的教师和学生，我很高兴地宣布，《论证规则手册》的配套教材现已出版。这本教材由我和大卫·莫罗共同撰写，名为《论证练习册》。练习册包含了《论证规则手册》的全部内容，并在每节课之间穿插了更详细的解释、丰富的示例和练习，以及精选的参考答案。非常感谢莫罗教授说服我和哈克特出版社认识到这本教材的必要性和吸引力，并承担了大部分的编写工作，使其得以出版两版（第一版于2013年出版；第二版于2016年出版）。大卫的真知灼见和建议也对新版《论证规则手册》的编写起到了重要作用。
Among related changes is that a few of the more challenging examples and themes in previous editions of Rulebook , most notably philosopher David Hume’s challenges to some of the usual arguments for the existence of God, are migrating to Workbook, where they can be treated in more depth. In many ways, Workbook is a {xi} natural follow-up to Rulebook, even if you are not in a class that requires it. We hope you will have a look.
相关变化之一是，《规则手册》先前版本中一些更具挑战性的例子和主题，尤其是哲学家大卫·休谟对一些常见上帝存在论证的挑战，将被移至《练习册》中，以便进行更深入的探讨。在许多方面，《练习册》都是《规则手册》的自然延伸，即使您并非就读于要求使用《规则手册》的课程。我们希望您能阅读一下。
By now it is a long list of colleagues, students, family members, and friends who have contributed thoughts, suggestions, or provocations to this and previous editions of Rulebook . This time around I would like to single out Deborah Wilkes, president and publisher, and her colleagues at Hackett Publishing Company, whose stalwart support and gentle encouragement has made both Rulebook and Workbook continuously enjoyable and superlatively produced projects. My continuing gratitude to you all!
如今，为《规则手册》及其前几版贡献想法、建议或启发的同事、学生、家人和朋友名单已经很长了。这一次，我要特别感谢哈克特出版社的总裁兼出版人黛博拉·威尔克斯及其同事，正是他们坚定不移的支持和悉心鼓励，才使得《规则手册》和《练习册》始终保持着极高的水准，并不断推出精彩纷呈的佳作。在此，我衷心感谢各位！
Anthony Weston
安东尼·韦斯顿
July 2017
2017年7月
#↩
{xiii} Introduction
{xiii} 引言
What’s the point of arguing?
争论有什么意义呢？
Many people think that arguing is simply stating their prejudices in a new form. This is why many people also think that arguments are unpleasant and pointless. One dictionary definition for “argument” is “disputation.” In this sense we sometimes say that two people “ have an argument”: a verbal fistfight. It happens often enough. But it is not what arguments really are.
许多人认为争论不过是换一种方式表达自己的偏见。正因如此，许多人也觉得争论既令人不快又毫无意义。词典中对“争论”的定义之一是“辩论”。在这个意义上，我们有时会说两个人“争论”：一场言语上的交锋。这种情况确实很常见。但这并非争论的真正含义。
In this book, “to give an argument” means to offer a set of reasons or evidence in support of a conclusion. Here an argument is not simply a statement of certain views, and it is not simply a dispute. Arguments are efforts to support certain views with reasons. Arguments in this sense are not pointless. In fact, they are essential.
本书中，“提出论点”指的是提供一系列理由或证据来支持某个结论。这里的论点并非仅仅是对某些观点的陈述，也并非仅仅是争论。论点是用理由来支持某些观点的努力。从这个意义上讲，论点并非毫无意义，事实上，它们至关重要。
Argument is essential, in the first place, because it is a way of finding out which views are better than others. Not all views are equal. Some conclusions can be supported by good reasons. Others have much weaker support. But often we don’t know which are which. We need to give arguments for different conclusions and then assess those arguments to see how strong they really are.
首先，论证至关重要，因为它能帮助我们找出哪些观点优于其他观点。并非所有观点都同等重要。有些结论有充分的理由支持，而另一些结论则缺乏足够的论据支撑。但我们往往无法分辨哪些结论更有说服力，哪些结论缺乏说服力。因此，我们需要为不同的结论提出论据，然后评估这些论据的可靠性。
Here argument is a means of inquiry. Some philosophers and activists have argued, for instance, that the factory farming of animals for meat causes immense suffering to animals and is therefore unjustified and immoral. Are they right? We can’t necessarily tell just by consulting our current opinions. Many issues are involved—we need to examine the arguments. Do we have moral obligations to other species, for instance, or is only human suffering really bad? How well can humans live without meat? Some vegetarians have lived to very old ages. Does this show that vegetarian diets are healthier? Or is it irrelevant when you consider that some nonvegetarians also have lived to very old ages? (You might make some progress by asking {xiv} whether vegetarians live to old age at a higher rate. ) Or might healthier people tend to become vegetarians, rather than vice versa? All of these questions need to be considered carefully, and the answers are not clear in advance.
在此，论证是一种探究手段。例如，一些哲学家和活动家认为，工厂化养殖动物以获取肉类会给动物带来巨大的痛苦，因此是不合理且不道德的。他们的观点正确吗？我们不能仅仅根据我们目前的看法来判断。这其中涉及诸多问题——我们需要审视这些论证。例如，我们是否对其他物种负有道德义务？或者只有人类的痛苦才是真正糟糕的？人类不吃肉也能生活得如何？一些素食者活到了很高的年纪。这是否表明素食更健康？或者，考虑到一些非素食者也活到了很高的年纪，这是否就无关紧要了？（你可以尝试询问{xiv}素食者的长寿率是否更高。）或者，更健康的人更容易成为素食者，而不是反过来？所有这些问题都需要仔细考虑，答案并非事先就显而易见。
Argument is essential for another reason too. Once we have arrived at a conclusion that is well supported by reasons, we use arguments to explain and defend it. A good argument doesn’t merely repeat conclusions. Instead it offers reasons and evidence so that other people can make up their minds for themselves. If you become convinced that we should indeed change the way we raise and use animals, for example, you must use arguments to explain how you arrived at your conclusion. That is how you will convince others: by offering the reasons and evidence that convinced you. It is not a mistake to have strong views. The mistake is to have nothing else.
论证之所以至关重要，还有另一个原因。一旦我们得出有充分理由支持的结论，我们就需要运用论证来解释和捍卫它。好的论证并非简单地重复结论，而是提供理由和证据，以便他人能够自行判断。例如，如果你确信我们应该改变饲养和利用动物的方式，你就必须运用论证来解释你是如何得出这个结论的。这才是说服他人的方法：提供那些让你信服的理由和证据。持有坚定的观点并非错误，错误在于除此之外别无其他。
Argument grows on you
争论会让你越陷越深。
Typically we learn to “argue” by assertion. That is, we tend to start with our conclusions—our desires or opinions—without a whole lot to back them up. And it works, sometimes, at least when we’re very young. What could be better?
我们通常通过断言来“辩论”。也就是说，我们倾向于从结论——我们的愿望或观点——出发，而缺乏足够的论据来支撑它们。有时，至少在我们年幼的时候，这种方法确实有效。还有什么比这更好呢？
Real argument, by contrast, takes time and practice. Marshaling our reasons, proportioning our conclusions to the actual evidence, considering objections, and all the rest—these are acquired skills. We have to grow up a little. We have to put aside our desires and our opinions for a while and actually think.
相比之下，真正的论证需要时间和练习。组织论据、使结论与实际证据相符、考虑反对意见等等——这些都是需要学习的技能。我们需要成熟一些。我们需要暂时放下自己的欲望和成见，认真思考。
School may help—or not. In courses concerned with teaching ever-larger sets of facts or techniques, students are seldom encouraged to ask the sorts of questions that arguments answer. Sure, our Constitution mandates the Electoral College—that’s a fact—but is it still a good idea? (For that matter, was it ever a good idea? What were the reasons for it, anyway?) Sure, many scientists believe that there is life elsewhere in the universe, but why? What’s the argument? Reasons can be given for different answers. In the end, ideally, you will not only learn some of those reasons but also learn how to weigh them up—and how to seek out more yourself.
学校教育或许有所帮助，也或许无济于事。在那些旨在教授越来越多事实或技巧的课程中，学生很少被鼓励去提出那些需要通过论证来解答的问题。诚然，我们的宪法规定了选举人团制度——这是事实——但它现在仍然是个好主意吗？（就此而言，它曾经是个好主意吗？它存在的理由究竟是什么？）诚然，许多科学家相信宇宙中其他地方存在生命，但为什么？他们的论证是什么？不同的答案都有各自的理由。最终，理想情况下，你不仅会了解其中的一些理由，还会学会如何权衡这些理由——以及如何自己去寻找更多答案。
{xv} Mostly, again, it takes time and practice. This book can help! Moreover, the practice of argument turns out to have some attractions of its own. Our minds become more flexible, open-ended, and alert. We come to appreciate how much difference our own critical thinking can really make. From everyday family life to politics, science, philosophy, and even religion, arguments are constantly offered to us for our consideration, and we may in turn offer back our own. Think of argument as a way to make your own place within these unfolding, ongoing dialogues. What could be better than that?
{xv} 归根结底，这需要时间和练习。这本书能帮到你！此外，辩论练习本身也颇具吸引力。我们的思维会变得更加灵活、开放和敏锐。我们会逐渐意识到批判性思维的重要性。从日常家庭生活到政治、科学、哲学，乃至宗教，我们不断地被各种论点所包围，而我们也可以反过来提出自己的观点。不妨把辩论看作是在这些不断发展、持续进行的对话中找到自己位置的一种方式。还有什么比这更棒的呢？
Outline of this book
本书概要
This book begins by discussing fairly simple arguments, moving then to extended arguments and their use in essays, oral presentations, and finally to public debates.
本书首先讨论较为简单的论证，然后逐步深入到论证的扩展及其在论文、口头报告以及最终在公共辩论中的应用。
Chapters I–VI are about composing and assessing short arguments. Short arguments simply offer their reasons and evidence briefly, usually in a few sentences or a paragraph. We begin with short arguments for several reasons. First, they are common: in fact so common that they are part of every day’s conversation. Second, longer arguments are usually elaborations of short arguments, or a series of short arguments linked together. If you learn to write and assess short arguments first, then you can extend your skills to longer arguments in essays or presentations.
第一章至第六章主要讲解如何撰写和评估简短论证。简短论证简明扼要地陈述理由和证据，通常用几句话或一段话概括。我们首先学习简短论证的原因有几个。首先，它们很常见：事实上，它们非常常见，几乎是日常对话的一部分。其次，较长的论证通常是对简短论证的阐述，或是由一系列简短论证串联而成。如果你先学会撰写和评估简短论证，那么你就可以将这些技能运用到论文或演讲等更长的论证中。
A third reason for beginning with short arguments is that they are the best illustrations both of the common argument forms and of the typical mistakes in arguments. In longer arguments, it can be harder to pick out the main points—and the main problems. Therefore, although some of the rules may seem obvious when first stated, remember that you have the benefit of a simple example. Other rules are hard enough to appreciate even in short arguments.
第三个选择从简短论证入手的原因是，它们最能体现常见的论证形式和论证中常见的错误。在较长的论证中，很难抓住要点和主要问题。因此，尽管有些规则乍看之下显而易见，但请记住，你拥有简单示例的帮助。而有些规则即使在简短的论证中也很难理解。
Chapter VII guides you into sketching and then elaborating an extended argument, considering objections and alternatives as you do. Chapter VIII guides you from there into writing an argumentative essay. Chapter IX then adds rules specifically about oral presentation, and Chapter X about public debate. Again, all of these {xvi} chapters depend on Chapters I–VI, since extended arguments like these essentially combine and elaborate the kinds of short arguments that Chapters I–VI discuss. Don’t skip ahead to the later chapters, then, even if you come to this book primarily for help writing an essay or doing a presentation. The book is short enough that you can read it through from the beginning, so that when you arrive at those later chapters you will have the tools you need to use them well. Instructors might wish to assign Chapters I–VI early in the term and Chapters VII–X when the time comes for essays and public presentations and debates.
第七章指导你如何勾勒并扩展论证，并在过程中考虑反对意见和替代方案。第八章在此基础上指导你撰写议论文。第九章专门介绍口头陈述的规则，第十章则介绍公开辩论。同样，所有这些章节都依赖于第一章至第六章，因为这些扩展论证本质上是对第一章至第六章所讨论的短论证类型的结合和扩展。因此，即使你主要是为了获得论文写作或演讲方面的帮助而阅读本书，也不要直接跳到后面的章节。本书篇幅适中，你可以从头开始通读，这样当你阅读到后面的章节时，就能掌握所需的工具。教师可以考虑在学期初布置第一章至第六章的作业，并在需要撰写论文、进行公开演讲或辩论时布置第七章至第十章的作业。
Two appendices close out the book. The first is a listing of fallacies: types of misleading arguments that are so tempting and common, they even have their own names. The second offers three rules for constructing and evaluating definitions. Use them when you need them!
本书最后附有两个附录。第一个附录列举了各种谬误：这些误导性论证类型既常见又极具诱惑力，甚至还有专门的名称。第二个附录提供了构建和评估定义的三个规则。需要时请运用它们！
#↩
{1} I
{1} 我
Short Arguments 简短论证
Some General Rules
一些通用规则
Arguments begin by marshaling reasons and organizing them in a clear and fair way. Chapter I offers general rules for composing short arguments. Chapters II–VI discuss specific kinds of short arguments.
论证始于梳理理由，并以清晰公正的方式组织这些理由。第一章提供了撰写简短论证的一般规则。第二章至第六章讨论了各种类型的简短论证。
1
Resolve premises and conclusion 解决前提和结论
The very first step in making an argument is to ask yourself what you are trying to prove. What is your conclusion? Remember that the conclusion is the statement for which you are giving reasons. The statements that give your reasons are your premises.
论证的第一步是问问自己：你要证明什么？你的结论是什么？记住，结论是你用来论证的陈述。而那些用来论证的陈述，就是你的前提。
Let’s say that you want to persuade your friends (or children, or parents, or …) to eat more beans. Probably this does not seem like the world’s most promising proposition, or the most important either. But it is a good first illustration—and diet does matter! Let’s consider how you might make such an argument.
假设你想说服你的朋友（或者孩子、父母等等）多吃豆子。这听起来可能不是世界上最有希望的提议，也不是最重要的。但这是一个很好的例子——饮食确实很重要！让我们来看看你该如何提出这样的论点。
You have your conclusion: we should eat more beans. That is your belief. But why? What are your reasons ? You may need to state them for yourself, for clarity first of all, and then to check that they really are good reasons. Certainly you have to state good reasons clearly if you expect others to agree or to change how they eat.
你的结论是：我们应该多吃豆类。这是你的想法。但是为什么呢？你的理由是什么？你或许需要先理清思路，然后再确认这些理由是否充分。当然，如果你希望别人同意你的观点或改变他们的饮食习惯，就必须清晰地阐述充分的理由。
So again: What are your reasons? One main premise probably is that beans are healthy: higher in fibers and protein and lower in fat and cholesterol than what most people eat now. So, properly supplemented, a diet of more beans could lead to a longer and more active life. You may not want to assume that your friends or family have heard, or really appreciated, this reason before—at least it is useful to be reminded.
所以，再说一遍：你的理由是什么？一个主要前提可能是豆类有益健康：与大多数人现在的饮食相比，豆类富含纤维和蛋白质，脂肪和胆固醇含量更低。因此，如果搭配适当的营养补充剂，多吃豆类的饮食可以带来更长寿、更健康的生活。你或许不应该想当然地认为你的朋友或家人以前听说过或真正理解这个理由——但至少提醒一下总是有益的。
{2} To get people motivated, it would be helpful to add another main premise as well. Since beans are often stereotyped as boring, why not also argue that bean dishes actually can be varied and exciting? Give some examples, your own favorite bean dishes maybe: spicy black bean taco fillings, for instance, and hummus (made from garbanzo beans). Now you’ve got an argument—good solid reasons for a clear conclusion.
{2} 为了激发大家的积极性，不妨再补充一个主要前提。既然豆类常被认为乏味，何不也论证一下豆类菜肴其实可以丰富多样、令人兴奋呢？举几个例子，比如你自己最喜欢的豆类菜肴：例如，辣味黑豆玉米饼馅料，以及鹰嘴豆泥（用鹰嘴豆制成）。这样你就有了论证——充分的理由，可以得出清晰的结论。
Even jokes can be arguments, though the reasons may seem silly.
即使是玩笑也可以成为论点，尽管理由可能看起来很愚蠢。
Living on earth may be tough, but it includes a free ride around the sun every year. 1
生活在地球上或许艰难，但每年都能免费绕太阳公转一圈。
Getting a free ride around the sun is not the sort of reason you normally expect for bearing up when life gets tough. That’s what makes the joke funny. But it is still a reason: an attempt to justify the claim that life isn’t quite so bad as it may sometimes seem. It’s a funny argument.
免费绕太阳转一圈，这可不是人们通常会想到用来支撑自己度过人生难关的理由。这正是这个笑话的笑点所在。但它仍然是一种理由：试图证明生活并没有想象中那么糟糕。这真是一个滑稽的论点。
In Rule 1— Resolve premises and conclusion—the word “resolve” has two related meanings. One is to distinguish them. Your reasons are different from your conclusion: keep them clearly separate. Getting a free ride around the sun is a distinct idea from bearing up when life gets tough, and it logically comes first. It’s a premise. Being better able to bear up might be something that follows. It’s a conclusion.
在规则 1——区分前提和结论——中，“区分”一词有两个相关的含义。其一是区分它们。你的理由与你的结论不同：务必将它们清晰地分开。免费绕太阳一周与在生活艰难时坚持下去是截然不同的概念，而且从逻辑上讲，前者先于后者。这是一个前提。而更好地坚持下去可能是其后续发展。这是一个结论。
Once you have distinguished your premises and conclusion, be sure that both are claims that you want to commit to. This is the other meaning of “resolve.” If so, proceed. If not, change them! In any case, being clear to yourself is necessary before you can be clear to anyone else.
一旦你区分了前提和结论，务必确保两者都是你真正想要坚持的主张。这就是“决心”的另一种含义。如果是，那就继续。如果不是，那就修改它们！总之，只有先让自己思路清晰，才能让别人明白。
This book offers you a ready list of different forms that arguments can take. Use this list to develop your premises. To defend a generalization, for instance, check Chapter II. It will remind you that you need to give a series of examples as premises, and it will tell you what sorts of examples to look for. If your conclusion requires a deductive argument like those explained in Chapter VI, the rules outlined in that chapter will tell you what types of premises you need. You may have to try several different arguments before you find one that works well.
本书提供了一份论证形式的清单，供您参考。您可以利用这份清单来构建前提。例如，要论证一个概括性的结论，请查阅第二章。第二章会提醒您，需要提供一系列例子作为前提，并告诉您应该寻找哪些类型的例子。如果您的结论需要像第六章中解释的那种演绎论证，那么该章概述的规则会告诉您需要哪些类型的前提。您可能需要尝试几种不同的论证方法，才能找到一个行之有效的。
{3}
2
Unfold your ideas in a natural order 按自然顺序展开你的想法
Arguments move. Reasons and evidence lead to conclusions. But, like any other form of movement, arguments may be graceful or clumsy, sharp or confused, clean or muddled. You want clarity and efficiency—even grace, if you can manage it.
论证是动态的。理由和证据最终会得出结论。但是，如同任何其他形式的运动一样，论证也可能优雅或笨拙，犀利或混乱，清晰或含糊。你追求的是清晰和高效——如果可以的话，甚至还要兼具优雅。
Take the argument about beans once more. If you were now going to write your argument out, how might you do it? One good way would be this:
再以关于豆子的争论为例。如果你现在要把你的论点写出来，你会怎么做呢？一个好方法是这样的：
We should eat more beans. One reason is that beans are healthy. They are higher in fibers and protein and lower in fat and cholesterol than what most people eat now. Meanwhile, bean dishes can be quite varied and exciting too. Think of spicy black bean taco fillings or hummus.
我们应该多吃豆类。原因之一是豆类有益健康。与大多数人现在的饮食相比，豆类富含纤维和蛋白质，脂肪和胆固醇含量更低。同时，豆类菜肴也种类繁多，令人垂涎。想想看，香辣黑豆玉米饼馅料或鹰嘴豆泥，是不是很棒？
Each sentence in this passage prepares the way for the next one, and then the next one steps smoothly up to bat. The argument begins by stating its conclusion. This invites stating premises in turn, and the argument obliges by immediately stating a main premise, and then giving a brief reason for it in turn, explaining why beans are healthy. Then it offers the other main premise and its examples. The argument could be laid out in different ways—for example, the second main premise could be first, and/or the conclusion could be drawn at the end rather than the beginning—but either way, each part is in a good place.
这段文字中的每一句话都为下一句铺垫，然后下一句自然而然地接踵而至。论证以陈述结论开篇。这促使作者依次陈述前提，而论证也顺应了这一思路，立即陈述了一个主要前提，并简要解释了豆类为何有益健康。接着，它提出了另一个主要前提及其例证。论证的展开方式可以有所不同——例如，可以将第二个主要前提放在开头，或者将结论放在结尾而非开头——但无论采用哪种方式，每个部分都恰到好处。
Getting an argument to unfold in this smooth way is an accomplishment, especially as arguments get more detailed and complex. It’s not easy to work out the right place for each part—and plenty of wrong places are usually available. For example, suppose we wrote the argument like this instead:
能够如此流畅地展开论证本身就是一项成就，尤其是在论证变得越来越详细和复杂时。要为每个部分找到合适的位置并不容易——而且通常有很多错误的位置可供选择。例如，假设我们这样写论证：
Think of spicy black bean taco fillings or hummus. Beans are higher in fibers and protein and lower in fat and cholesterol than what most people eat now. Bean dishes can be quite varied and exciting. We should eat more beans. Beans are healthy.
想想香辣黑豆玉米饼馅料或鹰嘴豆泥。豆类比大多数人现在吃的食物富含纤维和蛋白质，脂肪和胆固醇含量更低。豆类菜肴种类繁多，令人垂涎。我们应该多吃豆类。豆类有益健康。
{4} These are the same premises and conclusion, but they are in a different order, and the passage leaves out the signposts and transition words that help readers identify premises and conclusions (such as “one reason is that …”). The result is that the argument is totally garbled. The examples for the main premises, like how tasty bean dishes can be, are scattered through the passage rather than cited right next to the statement of those premises. You have to read the passage twice just to be sure what the conclusion is. Don’t count on your readers to be so patient.
{4} 前提和结论虽然相同，但顺序不同，而且文章省略了帮助读者识别前提和结论的提示词和过渡词（例如“其中一个原因是……”）。结果导致论证完全混乱。主要前提的例子，例如豆类菜肴有多美味，散落在文章各处，而不是直接与前提陈述并列。你必须读两遍才能确定结论是什么。别指望你的读者有这么大的耐心。
Expect to rearrange your argument several times to find the most natural order. Again, the rules offered in this book should help. You can use them to figure out not only what kinds of premises you need but also how to arrange them in the best order.
预计你需要多次调整论证顺序，才能找到最自然的排列方式。本书提供的规则应该会有所帮助。你可以利用这些规则，不仅确定你需要哪些前提，还能找到最佳的排列顺序。
3
Start from reliable premises 从可靠的前提开始
No matter how well you argue from premises to conclusion, your conclusion will be weak if your premises are weak.
无论你的论证过程多么严密，从前提推导出结论，如果你的前提本身就很薄弱，那么你的结论也会很薄弱。
Nobody in the world today is really happy. Therefore, it seems that human beings are just not made for happiness. Why should we expect what we can never find?
当今世界，没有人真正快乐。因此，似乎人类天生就不是为了快乐而生的。我们又何必期待永远无法得到的东西呢？
The premise of this argument is the statement that nobody in the world today is really happy. Sometimes, on certain rainy afternoons or in certain moods, this may almost seem true. But ask yourself if this premise really is plausible. Is nobody in the world today really happy? Ever? What about that free ride around the sun every year?
这个论点的前提是：当今世界没有人真正快乐。有时，在某些阴雨绵绵的午后，或在某些特定的情绪下，这似乎近乎正确。但请扪心自问，这个前提真的合理吗？当今世界真的没有人真正快乐吗？曾经有人快乐过吗？那么，每年绕太阳公转一周的免费旅程又该如何解释呢？
At the very least, this premise needs some serious defense, and very likely it is just not true. This argument cannot show, then, that human beings are not made for happiness or that you or I should not expect to be happy.
至少，这个前提需要认真论证，而且很可能它本身就是错误的。因此，这个论点并不能证明人类天生不追求幸福，也不能证明你我不应该期待幸福。
Sometimes it is easy to start from reliable premises. You may have well-known examples at hand or reliable sources that are clearly in agreement. Other times it is harder. If you are not sure about the reliability of a premise, you may need to do some research and/or {5} give an argument for the premise itself (see Rule 31 for more on this point). If you find you cannot argue adequately for your premise(s), then, of course, you need to try some other premise!
有时，从可靠的前提出发很容易。你可能手头就有众所周知的例子，或者有明确一致的可靠来源。但有时就比较困难了。如果你不确定某个前提的可靠性，你可能需要做一些研究，或者{5}为该前提本身提供论证（关于这一点，请参见规则31）。如果你发现自己无法充分论证你的前提，那么当然，你需要尝试其他的前提！
4
Be concrete and concise 要具体简洁。
Avoid abstract, vague, and general terms. “We hiked for hours in the sun” is a hundred times better than “It was an extended period of laborious exertion.” Be concise too. Airy elaboration just loses everyone in a fog of words.
避免使用抽象、模糊和笼统的词语。“我们在阳光下徒步了几个小时”比“这是一段漫长而艰苦的劳作”要好一百倍。还要力求简洁。冗长的描述只会让读者陷入文字的迷雾中。
NO:
不：
Regularly turning in for the night at an hour that precedes the time at which most of your compatriots go to bed, combined with the practice of awakening at an hour that is earlier than the hour at which most others arise, will tend to the acquisition of such desirable personal traits as a resilient physical constitution, a comfortably well-established financial situation, and the sort of intellectual abilities and capacity for sagacious discernment and judgment that tend to be conducive to earning the respect of others.
经常在大多数同胞入睡前一小时就寝，并在大多数人起床前一小时起床，将有助于获得一些令人向往的个人特质，例如强健的体魄、稳定的经济状况，以及有助于赢得他人尊重的智力、洞察力和判断力。
YES:
是的：
Early to bed and early to rise makes a man healthy, wealthy, and wise.
早睡早起使人健康、富有、聪明。
The “No” version might overdo it just a bit (you think?), but you see the point. Ben Franklin’s rhyme and rhythm help too, but the most important thing is that his words are sharp, simple, and few.
“不”的版本可能有点用力过猛（你觉得呢？），但你明白我的意思。本杰明·富兰克林的韵律也功不可没，但最重要的是，他的言辞简洁有力，言简意赅。
{6}
5
Build on substance, not overtone 注重实质，而非空洞言辞
Offer actual reasons; don’t just play on the overtones of words.
给出实际理由；不要玩弄文字游戏。
NO:
不：
Having so disgracefully allowed her once-proud passenger railroads to fade into obscurity, America is honor-bound to restore them now!
美国曾如此可耻地任由其曾经引以为傲的客运铁路走向衰落，如今美国有义务恢复它们！
This is supposed to be an argument for restoring (more) passenger rail service. But it offers no evidence for this conclusion whatsoever, just some emotionally loaded words—shopworn words, too, like a politician on automatic. Did passenger rail “fade” because of something “America” did or didn’t do? What was “disgraceful” about this? Many “once-proud” institutions outlive their times, after all—we’re not obliged to restore them all. What does it mean to say America is “honor-bound” to do this? Have promises been made and broken? By whom?
这篇论述本意是支持恢复（更多）客运铁路服务，但它完全没有提供任何证据来支持这一结论，只是一些情绪化的言辞——而且是老生常谈，就像政客机械地重复着陈词滥调。客运铁路的“衰落”是因为“美国”做了什么或没做什么吗？这其中有什么“可耻”之处？毕竟，许多“曾经辉煌”的机构都会随着时代变迁而消亡——我们没有义务去恢复它们。说美国“有义务”这样做到底是什么意思？有人做出过承诺又违背过吗？是谁违背的？
Much can be said for restoring passenger rail, especially in this era when the ecological and economic costs of highways are becoming enormous. The problem is that this argument does not say it. It lets the emotional charge of the words do all the work, and therefore really does no work at all. We’re left exactly where we started. Overtones may sometimes persuade even when they shouldn’t, of course—but remember, here we are looking for actual, concrete evidence.
恢复客运铁路有很多好处，尤其是在高速公路生态和经济成本日益巨大的今天。问题在于，这种论证方式并没有真正阐明这一点。它让言辞的情感力量发挥作用，结果却适得其反。我们最终还是回到了原点。当然，言外之意有时或许能起到说服作用，即便不应该如此——但请记住，我们在这里寻求的是实际的、具体的证据。
Likewise, do not try to make your argument look good by using emotionally loaded words to label the other side. Generally, people advocate a position for serious and sincere reasons. Try to figure out their view—try to understand their reasons —even if you disagree entirely. For example, people who question a new technology are probably not in favor of “going back to the caves.” (What are they in favor of? Maybe you need to ask.) Likewise, a person who believes in evolution is not claiming that her grandparents were monkeys. (And again: what does she think?) In general, if you can’t imagine how anyone could hold the view you are attacking, you probably just don’t understand it yet.
同样，不要试图用带有强烈情感色彩的词语给对方贴标签来美化你的论点。通常，人们支持某种立场都是出于严肃而真诚的理由。即使你完全不同意，也要试着理解他们的观点和理由。例如，质疑一项新技术的人可能并不赞成“回到洞穴生活”。（他们赞成什么呢？或许你需要问问。）同样，相信进化论的人并不是在声称她的祖父母是猴子。（再说一遍：她自己是怎么想的？）总的来说，如果你无法想象有人会持有你正在攻击的观点，那很可能只是因为你还没有真正理解它。
{7}
6
Use consistent terms 使用一致的术语
Short arguments normally have a single theme or thread. They carry one idea through several steps. Therefore, couch that idea in clear and carefully chosen terms, and mark each new step by using those very same terms again.
简短的论证通常只有一个主题或线索。它们通过几个步骤来阐述一个观点。因此，要用清晰且精心选择的措辞来表达这个观点，并在每个新的步骤中再次使用这些措辞。
In their classic composition handbook, The Elements of Style, William Strunk and E. B. White cite Jesus’s famous Beatitudes as a compelling illustration of what they call “parallel construction” or “expressing coordinate ideas in similar form.”
在他们的经典写作手册《风格的要素》中，威廉·斯特伦克和E·B·怀特引用耶稣著名的八福作为他们所谓的“平行结构”或“以相似的形式表达共同思想”的有力例证。
Blessed are the poor in spirit: for theirs is the kingdom of Heaven.
虚心的人有福了，因为天国是他们的。
Blessed are those who mourn: for they will be comforted.
哀恸的人有福了，因为他们必得安慰。
Blessed are the meek: for they will inherit the earth … (Matthew 5:3–5)
温柔的人有福了，因为他们必承受地土……（马太福音 5:3-5）
“Blessed are the X: for Y” is the formula. It is not rephrased in each case, like “Also, those who are X will be consecrated, because Y.” Instead, each sentence has exactly the same structure and exactly the same phrasing.
“X有福了，因为Y”是固定的公式。它不会像“此外，那些X的人也将被分别为圣，因为Y”那样逐句改写。相反，每句话的结构和措辞都完全相同。
Do the same for your arguments.
对你的论点也进行同样的处理。
NO:
不：
When you learn to care for a pet, you learn to attend to the needs of a dependent creature. Watching and responding carefully when a cat or a dog needs you, your ability to recognize needs and adjust your behavior accordingly can improve toward young children as well. Becoming a more responsive keeper of domestic animals can therefore enhance your familial caregiving skills too.
当你学会照顾宠物时，你也就学会了如何照料依赖你的生命。当你细心观察并及时回应猫狗的需求时，你识别它们需求并相应地调整自身行为的能力也会得到提升，这同样有助于你更好地照顾年幼的孩子。因此，成为一个更善解人意的家养动物主人也能增强你的家庭照护能力。
Huh? Each sentence may be fairly clear by itself, but the connections between them are totally lost in the underbrush—interesting underbrush, maybe, but too thick for moving effectively. (Remember, arguments need to move !)
嗯？每句话单独来看或许都挺清楚，但它们之间的联系却完全被淹没在冗杂的论述中——或许这些论述本身很有趣，但却过于密集，难以有效推进。（记住，论证需要逻辑推进！）
{8} YES:
{8} 是：
When you learn to care for a pet, you learn to attend to the needs of a dependent creature. When you learn to attend to the needs of a dependent creature, you learn to be a better parent. Therefore, when you learn to care for a pet, you learn to be a better parent.
学会照顾宠物，就等于学会了如何照料需要依赖你的生命。学会照料需要依赖你的生命，就等于学会了如何成为更好的父母。因此，学会照顾宠物，就等于学会了如何成为更好的父母。
The “Yes” version might not be stylish in a flowery way, but it more than makes up for that by being absolutely crystal clear. One simple feature makes the difference: the “No” version uses a new phrase for each key idea every time the idea recurs—for example, “When you learn to care for a pet” is described again in the “No” version’s conclusion as “Becoming a more responsive keeper of domestic animals”—whereas the “Yes” argument carefully and exactly repeats its key terms.
“是”的版本或许不够华丽，但它清晰明了，足以弥补这一点。一个简单的特点决定了二者的区别：“否”的版本每次重复出现某个关键概念时都会使用新的短语——例如，“当你学会照顾宠物”在“否”的结论中被描述为“成为一个更负责任的家畜饲养者”——而“是”的论证则一丝不苟地重复其关键术语。
If you are concerned about style—as sometimes you should be, of course—then go for the tightest argument, not the most flowery.
如果你注重文风——当然，有时候你应该注重文风——那么就选择最严谨的论证，而不是最华丽的辞藻。
MOST CONCISE:
最简洁：
When you learn to care for a pet, you learn to attend to the needs of a dependent creature, and therefore in turn learn to be a better parent.
当你学会照顾宠物时，你就学会了照顾一个需要依赖你的生命体的需求，因此反过来，你也会学会成为一个更好的父母。
