#↩
{9} II
{9} II
Arguments by Example 以实例论证
Some arguments offer one or more examples in support of a generalization.
有些论证会提供一个或多个例子来支持某种概括。
Women in earlier times were married very young. Juliet in Shakespeare’s Romeo and Juliet was not even fourteen years old. In the Middle Ages, thirteen was the normal age of marriage for a Jewish woman. And during the Roman Empire, many Roman women were married at age thirteen or younger.
早期女性结婚年龄普遍很早。莎士比亚笔下的《罗密欧与朱丽叶》中的朱丽叶甚至还不到十四岁。中世纪时期，犹太女性的正常结婚年龄是十三岁。而在罗马帝国时期，许多罗马女性在十三岁甚至更小的时候就结婚了。
This argument generalizes from three examples—Juliet, Jewish women in the Middle Ages, and Roman women during the Roman Empire—to “many” or most women in earlier times. To show the form of this argument most clearly, we can list the premises separately, with the conclusion on the “bottom line”:
这个论证从三个例子——朱丽叶、中世纪的犹太女性和罗马帝国时期的罗马女性——概括到早期“许多”或大多数女性。为了更清晰地展示这个论证的形式，我们可以分别列出前提，并将结论放在最后：
Juliet in Shakespeare’s play was not even fourteen years old.
莎士比亚戏剧中的朱丽叶甚至还不到十四岁。
Jewish women during the Middle Ages were normally married at thirteen.
中世纪的犹太女性通常在十三岁结婚。
Many Roman women during the Roman Empire were married at age thirteen or younger.
罗马帝国时期，许多罗马女性在十三岁或更小的时候就结婚了。
Therefore, women in earlier times were married very young.
因此，古代女性结婚年龄普遍较小。
It is helpful to write short arguments in this way when we need to see exactly how they work.
当我们需要确切了解论证过程时，用这种方式写出简短的论证是有帮助的。
When do premises like these adequately support a generalization?
诸如此类的前提何时才能充分支持概括？
One requirement, of course, is that the examples be accurate. Remember Rule 3: start from reliable premises! If Juliet wasn’t around fourteen, or if most Roman or Jewish women weren’t married at thirteen or younger, then the argument is much weaker. If none of the premises can be supported, there is no argument at all. To check {10} an argument’s examples, or to find good examples for your own arguments, you may need to do some research.
当然，前提条件是例子必须准确。记住规则3：从可靠的前提出发！如果朱丽叶不是十四岁左右，或者大多数罗马或犹太女性不是在十三岁或更小的时候结婚，那么论证就弱得多。如果所有前提都无法得到支持，那么根本就不存在论证。为了检验论证的例子是否成立，或者为自己的论证找到合适的例子，你可能需要做一些研究。
But suppose the examples are accurate. Even then, generalizing from them is a tricky business. The rules in this chapter offer a short checklist for assessing arguments by example.
但假设这些例子是准确的，即便如此，从中得出普遍结论也并非易事。本章的规则提供了一个简短的清单，用于评估通过例子得出的论证。
7
Use more than one example 请举多个例子
A single example can sometimes be used for the sake of illustration. The example of Juliet alone might illustrate early marriage. But a single example offers next to no support for a generalization. Juliet alone may just be an exception. One spectacularly miserable billionaire does not prove that rich people in general are unhappy. One great meal at a new restaurant in town does not necessarily mean that its whole menu is first-rate. More than one example is needed.
为了便于说明，有时可以使用单个例子。例如，朱丽叶的例子或许可以说明早婚的弊端。但仅凭一个例子几乎无法得出普遍结论。朱丽叶可能只是个例外。一个极其痛苦的亿万富翁并不能证明富人普遍不快乐。在城里一家新餐厅吃到一顿美味佳肴，并不一定意味着它的所有菜品都一流。我们需要更多例子来佐证。
NO:
不：
Solar power is widely used.
太阳能得到了广泛应用。
Therefore, renewable energy is widely used.
因此，可再生能源得到了广泛应用。
Solar power is one form of renewable energy, but only one. What about others?
太阳能是可再生能源的一种形式，但只是其中之一。其他的呢？
YES:
是的：
Solar power is widely used.
太阳能得到了广泛应用。
Hydroelectric power has long been widely used.
水力发电长期以来一直被广泛应用。
Windmills were once widely used and are becoming widely used again.
风车曾经被广泛使用，现在又开始被广泛使用。
Therefore, renewable energy is widely used.
因此，可再生能源得到了广泛应用。
The “Yes” version may not be perfect (Rule 11 returns to it), but it certainly is more energetic, so to speak, than the “No” version.
“是”的版本可能并不完美（第 11 条规则又回到了这一点），但它肯定比“否”的版本更有活力。
{11} In a generalization about a small set of things, the strongest argument should consider all, or at least many, of the examples. A generalization about your siblings should consider each of them in turn, for instance, and a generalization about all the planets in the solar system can do the same.
{11} 在对一小部分事物进行概括时，最有力的论证应该考虑所有或至少大部分例子。例如，对你的兄弟姐妹进行概括时，应该依次考虑他们每个人；对太阳系所有行星进行概括时，也可以这样做。
Generalizations about larger sets of things require picking out a sample. We cannot list all women in earlier times who married young. Instead, our argument must offer a few women in earlier times as a sample of all women in earlier times. How many examples are required depends partly on how representative they are, a point the next rule takes up. It also depends partly on the size of the set being generalized about. Large sets usually require more examples. The claim that your town is full of remarkable people requires more evidence than the claim that, say, your friends are remarkable people. Depending on how many friends you have, even just two or three examples might be enough to establish that your friends are remarkable people; but, unless your town is tiny, many more examples are required to show that your town is full of remarkable people.
对较大集合进行概括需要选取样本。我们无法列出所有早婚女性。相反，我们的论证必须提供一些早期女性的例子，作为早期所有女性的样本。所需样本的数量部分取决于它们的代表性，这一点将在下一条规则中讨论。它还部分取决于被概括集合的大小。较大的集合通常需要更多的例子。例如，声称你的城镇里有很多杰出人士，比声称你的朋友都是杰出人士需要更多证据。根据你朋友的数量，即使只有两三个例子也可能足以证明你的朋友是杰出人士；但是，除非你的城镇很小，否则需要更多的例子才能证明你的城镇里有很多杰出人士。
8
Use representative examples 使用代表性例子
Even a large number of examples may misrepresent the set of things being generalized about. Do all insects bite, for example? Sure, we can think of lots of insects that do, like mosquitoes and black flies, and naturally those are the examples we think of first. After all, we are bugged by them! We may have to consult a biology textbook or a good online source to remember how many kinds of insects there are that don’t bite—which is most of them, actually: moths, praying mantis, ladybugs, (most) beetles, and so on.
即使列举大量例子，也可能无法准确概括事物的本质。例如，所有昆虫都会咬人吗？当然，我们能想到很多会咬人的昆虫，比如蚊子和黑蝇，而且这些自然是我们首先想到的例子。毕竟，我们都被它们烦得不行！我们可能需要查阅生物学教科书或可靠的在线资源，才能想起有多少种昆虫不会咬人——实际上，绝大多数昆虫都不会咬人：飞蛾、螳螂、瓢虫、（大多数）甲虫等等。
Likewise, a large number of examples of ancient Roman women establishes very little about women generally, since ancient Roman women are not necessarily representative of other women in earlier times. If we want to make a sweeping claim about women in earlier times, the argument needs to consider women from other early times and from other parts of the world as well.
同样，大量古罗马女性的例子并不能说明女性的普遍情况，因为古罗马女性未必能代表早期其他时代的女性。如果我们想对早期女性做出概括性的论断，就需要将其他早期时代以及世界其他地区的女性也纳入考量。
{12} It is easy to overlook how un representative—often wildly unrepresentative—our personal “samples” often are. Actually, very few if any of us really know a representative sample of other people. Yet we constantly generalize about other people as a group, such as when we make claims about “human nature,” or even how our town might vote in the next election.
{12} 我们很容易忽略我们个人“样本”的代表性有多么不足——往往是严重缺乏代表性。事实上，我们当中很少有人真正了解其他人群的代表性样本。然而，我们却不断地对其他人群进行概括，例如当我们对“人性”做出断言时，甚至当我们预测我们所在的城镇在下次选举中的投票倾向时。
NO:
不：
Everyone in my neighborhood favors the School Bond. Therefore, the School Bond is sure to pass.
我所在社区的每个人都支持学校债券。因此，学校债券肯定会通过。
This argument is weak because single neighborhoods seldom represent the voting population as a whole. A well-to-do neighborhood may favor a cause unpopular with everyone else. Student wards in university towns regularly are carried by candidates who do poorly elsewhere. Besides, we do not always have good evidence even about the views held in a specific neighborhood. The set of people eager to display their political preferences to the world in yard signs, for example, is unlikely to be a representative cross-section of the neighborhood as a whole.
这种论点站不住脚，因为单个社区很少能代表整个选民群体。一个富裕的社区可能支持其他社区不受欢迎的理念。大学城的学生选区经常由在其他选区表现不佳的候选人赢得。此外，即使是关于特定社区居民的观点，我们也并非总能掌握确凿的证据。例如，那些热衷于在自家院子里竖起竞选标语牌向外界展示政治倾向的人，不太可能代表整个社区的选民群体。
A good argument that “The School Bond is sure to win” requires a representative sample of the entire voting population. It is not easy to construct such a sample. In fact, it usually takes professional help, and even professional pollsters regularly predict elections incorrectly. Telephone pollsters used to call landlines, for example, because cell phone numbers are not as publicly accessible; but only certain demographic groups still have landlines, and they are increasingly unrepresentative.
要得出“学校债券肯定会通过”的有力论据，需要一个能够代表全体选民的样本。构建这样的样本并非易事。事实上，这通常需要专业人士的帮助，而即使是专业的民调机构也经常会预测错误。例如，过去电话民调机构会拨打固定电话，因为手机号码不像固定电话那样容易获取；但如今只有特定人群仍然使用固定电话，而且这些人群的代表性越来越差。
In general, look for the most accurate cross-section you can find of the population being generalized about. If you want to know what students think about some subject at your university, don’t just ask your friends or generalize from what you hear in class. Unless you have quite a range of friends and take a wide range of classes, your personal sample is very unlikely to accurately mirror the whole student body. Similarly, if you want to know what people in other countries think about the United States, don’t just ask foreign tourists—for they, of course, are the ones who chose to come here. A careful look {13} at a diverse range of foreign media should give you a more representative picture.
一般来说，要寻找能够最准确地代表目标人群的样本。如果你想了解你所在大学的学生对某个学科的看法，不要只问你的朋友，也不要仅仅根据课堂上听到的内容进行概括。除非你的朋友范围很广，而且你选修的课程也很多，否则你的个人样本不太可能准确反映全体学生的观点。同样地，如果你想了解其他国家的人对美国的看法，不要只问外国游客——因为他们当然是自己选择来美国的。仔细查阅各种外国媒体{13}，应该能让你获得更具代表性的画面。
When your sample is people, an even more basic point is that no one should be able to self-select for it. This immediately disqualifies almost all online or mail-in polls to which individuals can decide whether to respond or not. Again, the set of people who are willing or eager to express their opinions is almost certainly not representative of the whole population, but are the people more likely to have strong opinions—or a lot of time on their hands. It may be interesting to know what that group thinks anyway, but not because they necessarily speak for anyone but themselves.
当你的样本是人时，一个更基本的原则是，任何人都不应该能够自愿选择参与。这立即排除了几乎所有允许个人自行决定是否作答的在线或邮寄民意调查。同样，那些愿意或渴望表达意见的人几乎肯定不能代表全体人口，但他们更有可能持有强烈的观点——或者有很多空闲时间。了解这个群体的想法或许很有趣，但这并非因为他们一定能代表其他人，而仅仅是因为他们自己。
9
Background rates are often crucial 背景率通常至关重要
To persuade you that I am a first-rate archer, it is not enough to show you a bull’s-eye I have made. You should ask (politely, to be sure), “Yes, but how many times did you miss ?” Getting a bull’s-eye in one shot tells quite a different story than getting a bull’s-eye in, say, a thousand, even though in both cases I genuinely do have a bull’s-eye to my name. You need a little more data.
要想让你相信我是个一流的射手，光给你看我射中靶心的照片是不够的。你应该问（当然要礼貌地问），“是啊，但你脱靶了多少次？”一箭命中靶心和射中一千次靶心，意义截然不同，即便这两种情况下我的确都射中过靶心。你需要更多信息。
Leon’s horoscope told him that he would meet a vivacious new stranger, and lo and behold he did! Therefore, horoscopes are reliable.
莱昂的星座运势告诉他，他会遇到一位活泼开朗的新朋友，果不其然，他真的遇到了！因此，星座运势是可靠的。
Dramatic as such an example may be, the problem is that we are only looking at one case in which a horoscope came true. To properly evaluate this evidence, we need to know something else as well: how many horoscopes didn’t come true. When I survey my classes, we can usually find a few Leons out of twenty or thirty students. It’s a fun moment. But the other nineteen or twenty-nine horoscopes go nowhere. A kind of prediction that comes true only once out of twenty or thirty tries is hardly reliable—it’s just lucky once in a while. It may have some dramatic successes, like my archery, but its success rate may still be abysmal.
这样的例子固然引人注目，但问题在于我们只看到了一个星座运势应验的案例。为了正确评估这一证据，我们还需要知道另一个信息：有多少星座运势没有应验。当我调查我的学生时，通常二三十个学生中能找到几个狮子座。这很有趣。但其他十九个或二十九个星座运势都毫无结果。一种预测方式，如果二三十次尝试中只有一次应验，那它就很难称得上可靠——它只是偶尔走运而已。它或许会有一些惊人的成功，比如我的射箭天赋，但它的准确率可能仍然低得可怜。
To evaluate the reliability of any argument featuring a few vivid examples, then, we need to know the ratio between the number of {14} “hits,” so to speak, and the number of tries. It’s a question of representativeness again. Are the featured examples the only ones there are? Is the rate impressively high or low?
因此，要评估任何包含少量生动例子的论证的可靠性，我们需要知道{14}个“命中”次数（姑且这么说）与尝试次数之间的比率。这又回到了代表性的问题。这些例子是唯一的例子吗？命中率是高得惊人还是低得惊人？
This rule is widely applicable. Today, many people live in fear of crime, or constantly attend to stories of shark attacks, terrorism, or other dramatic events. Of course these things are awful when they occur, but the probability of any of them actually happening to any given individual—say, the shark attack rate —is extremely low. Crime rates continue to go down.
这条规律适用范围很广。如今，许多人生活在对犯罪的恐惧之中，或者时刻关注着鲨鱼袭击、恐怖主义或其他耸人听闻的事件报道。当然，这些事情发生时固然可怕，但任何特定个体遭遇此类事件的概率——比如鲨鱼袭击的概率——都极低。犯罪率也持续下降。
No doubt we are preoccupied with the exceptions because they are constantly featured on TV and in the news. This does not mean that they are actually representative. The same goes, by the way, for desired things, like winning the lottery. Any individual’s chance of winning—that is, the winning rate —is so low as to be basically nil, but we seldom see the hundreds of thousands of losers, just the one or few winners raking in the money. So we wildly overestimate the background rates, and imagine that with the next lottery ticket purchase, we may be the one. Save your money, friends. Background rates make all the difference!
毫无疑问，我们之所以如此关注例外情况，是因为它们经常出现在电视和新闻中。但这并不意味着它们具有代表性。顺便一提，对于我们渴望的东西，比如中彩票，也是如此。任何个人的中奖概率——也就是中奖率——都低得几乎为零，但我们很少看到成千上万的失败者，看到的只是少数几个中奖者大赚一笔。因此，我们大大高估了中奖率，并幻想着下次买彩票时，自己就能成为那个幸运儿。朋友们，省省钱吧。中奖率才是关键！
10
Statistics need a critical eye 统计数据需要批判性审视。
You cannot “prove anything with numbers”! Some people see numbers—any numbers—in an argument and conclude from that fact alone that it must be a good argument. Statistics seem to have an aura of authority and definiteness (and did you know that 88 percent of doctors agree?). In fact, though, numbers take as much critical thinking as any other kind of evidence. Don’t turn off your brain!
你不能“用数字证明任何事情”！有些人看到论证中的数字——任何数字——就断定这一定是个好论证。统计数据似乎有一种权威和确定性的光环（你知道吗，88%的医生也认同这一点？）。但事实上，解读数字和其他任何证据一样，都需要批判性思维。别让你的大脑停止运转！
After an era when some athletic powerhouse universities were accused of exploiting student athletes, leaving them to flunk out once their eligibility expired, college athletes are now graduating at higher rates. Many schools are now graduating more than 50 percent of their athletes.
过去，一些体育强校曾被指控剥削学生运动员，导致他们在参赛资格到期后辍学。而如今，大学运动员的毕业率正在提高。许多学校的运动员毕业率已超过50%。
{15} Fifty percent, eh? Pretty impressive! But this figure, at first so persuasive, does not really do the job it claims to do.
{15} 百分之五十，嗯？相当惊人！但是这个数字，乍一看很有说服力，实际上并没有达到它所声称的效果。
First, although “many” schools graduate more than 50 percent of their athletes, it appears that some do not—so this figure may well exclude the most exploitative schools that really concerned people in the first place.
首先，虽然“很多”学校的运动员毕业率超过 50%，但似乎有些学校达不到这个标准——因此，这个数字很可能不包括那些最剥削运动员的学校，而这些学校才是人们最初真正关注的问题。
The argument does offer graduation rates. But it would be useful to know how a “more than 50 percent” graduation rate compares with the graduation rate for all students at the same institutions. If it is significantly lower, athletes may still be getting the shaft.
这种论证确实提到了毕业率。但我们需要了解“超过50%”的毕业率与同一院校所有学生的毕业率相比如何。如果后者明显低于所有学生的毕业率，那么运动员可能仍然处于不利地位。
Most importantly, this argument offers no reason to believe that college athletes’ graduation rates are actually improving, because no comparison to any previous rate is offered! The conclusion claims that the graduation rate is now “higher,” but without knowing the previous rates it is impossible to tell.
最重要的是，这种论点没有提供任何理由证明大学运动员的毕业率确实在提高，因为它没有提供任何与以往毕业率的比较数据！结论声称目前的毕业率“更高”，但如果不了解之前的毕业率，就无法做出判断。
Numbers may offer incomplete evidence in other ways too. Rule 9, for example, tells us that knowing background rates may be crucial. Correspondingly, when an argument offers rates or percentages, the relevant background information usually must include the number of examples. Car thefts on campus may have doubled, but if this means that two cars were stolen rather than one, there’s not much to worry about.
数字在其他方面也可能提供不完整的证据。例如，规则 9 告诉我们，了解背景比率可能至关重要。相应地，当论证中使用比率或百分比时，相关的背景信息通常必须包括示例的数量。校园内的汽车盗窃案可能翻了一番，但如果这意味着两辆车被盗而不是一辆，那就没什么好担心的。
Another statistical pitfall is over-precision :
另一个统计学陷阱是过度精确：
Every year this campus wastes 412,067 paper and plastic cups. It’s time to switch to reusable cups!
这个校园每年浪费412067个纸杯和塑料杯。是时候改用可重复使用的杯子了！
I’m all for ending waste too, and I’m sure the amount of campus waste is huge. But no one really knows the precise number of cups wasted—and it’s extremely unlikely to be exactly the same every year. Here the appearance of exactness makes the evidence seem more authoritative than it really is.
我也非常赞成杜绝浪费，而且我确信校园里的垃圾量巨大。但没人真正知道浪费了多少杯子——而且每年都完全相同的可能性微乎其微。在这里，看似精确的数据让证据显得比实际更有说服力。
Be wary, also, of numbers that are easily manipulated. Pollsters know very well that the way a question is asked can shape how it is answered. These days we are even seeing “polls” that try to change people’s minds about, say, a political candidate, just by asking loaded questions (“If you were to discover that she is a liar and a cheat, how would that change your vote?”). Then too, many apparently “hard” statistics are actually based on guesswork or extrapolation, such as {16} data about semi-legal or illegal activities. Since people have a major motive not to reveal or report things like drug use, under-the-counter transactions, hiring illegal aliens, and the like, beware of any confident generalizations about how widespread they are.
此外，还要警惕那些容易被操纵的数据。民调机构非常清楚，提问的方式会影响人们的回答。如今，我们甚至看到一些“民调”试图通过提出诱导性问题（例如，“如果你发现她是个骗子，你会如何改变投票意向？”）来改变人们对某个政治候选人的看法。此外，许多看似“可靠”的统计数据实际上也是基于猜测或推断，例如关于半合法或非法活动的数据{16}。由于人们有很大的动机不去透露或报告吸毒、私下交易、雇用非法移民等行为，因此要警惕任何关于这些行为普遍程度的自信概括。
Yet again:
又来了：
If kids keep watching more TV at current rates, by 2025 they’ll have no time left to sleep!
如果孩子们继续以目前的速度看电视，到 2025 年他们将没有时间睡觉了！
Right, and by 2040 they’ll be watching thirty-six hours a day. Extrapolation in such cases is perfectly possible mathematically, but after a certain point it tells you nothing.
没错，到2040年，他们每天要看36个小时的电视。在这种情况下，数学上完全可以进行推断，但超过某个临界点后，推断就毫无意义了。
11
Reckon with counterexamples 考虑反例
Counterexamples are examples that contradict your generalization. No fun—maybe. But counterexamples actually can be a generalizer’s best friends, if you use them early and use them well. Exceptions don’t “prove the rule”—quite the contrary, they threaten to dis prove it—but they can and should prompt us to refine it. Therefore, seek out counterexamples early and systematically. It is the best way to sharpen your own generalizations and to probe more deeply into your theme.
反例是指与你的概括相矛盾的例子。这听起来可能不太有趣，但如果你及早且恰当地运用反例，它们实际上可以成为概括者的最佳伙伴。例外情况并不能“证明规则”——恰恰相反，它们有可能推翻规则——但它们可以而且应该促使我们完善规则。因此，要尽早且系统地寻找反例。这是完善你的概括并更深入地探究主题的最佳途径。
Consider this argument once again:
请再次考虑以下论点：
Solar power is widely used.
太阳能得到了广泛应用。
Hydroelectric power has long been widely used.
水力发电长期以来一直被广泛应用。
Windmills were once widely used and are becoming widely used again.
风车曾经被广泛使用，现在又开始被广泛使用。
Therefore, renewable energy is widely used.
因此，可再生能源得到了广泛应用。
The examples here certainly do help to show that many renewable energy sources are widely used: sun, wind, and rain. However, as soon as you start thinking about counterexamples instead of just more examples, you may find that the argument somewhat overgeneralizes.
这里列举的例子确实有助于说明许多可再生能源得到了广泛应用，例如太阳能、风能和雨水。然而，一旦你开始思考反例而不是仅仅列举更多例子，你可能会发现这个论证在某种程度上过于笼统。
{17} Are all renewables widely used? Look up the definition of “renewable energy” and you will find that there are other types as well, such as the tides and geothermal energy (the internal heat of the earth). And these, for better or worse, are not so widely used. They aren’t available everywhere, for one thing, and may be difficult to harness even when available.
{17} 所有可再生能源都得到广泛应用吗？查阅“可再生能源”的定义，你会发现还有其他类型，例如潮汐能和地热能（地球内部的热能）。无论好坏，这些能源的应用并不广泛。首先，它们并非随处可得；其次，即使可得，也可能难以利用。
When you think of counterexamples to a generalization that you want to defend, then you need to adjust your generalization. If the renewable energy argument were yours, for instance, you might change the conclusion to “ Many forms of renewable energy are widely used.” Your argument still hits the high points, so to speak, while it acknowledges limits and the possibility for improvement in some areas.
当你想到要反驳某个你想捍卫的概括性论断的例子时，你就需要调整你的概括性论断。例如，如果你提出了关于可再生能源的论点，你可能会把结论改成“多种形式的可再生能源已被广泛应用”。这样，你的论证仍然抓住了要点，同时也承认了某些领域的局限性和改进空间。
Counterexamples should prompt you to think more deeply about what you actually want to say. For example, maybe your interest in arguing about renewables is to try to show that there are ready and workable alternatives to the usual non-renewable sources. If that is your aim, you don’t necessarily need to argue that all renewables are widely used. It is enough that some are. You might even urge that the ones that are less widely used be better developed.
反例应该促使你更深入地思考你真正想表达的观点。例如，你可能想论证可再生能源的可行性，并试图证明存在现成的、可行的替代方案来取代常见的不可再生能源。如果这是你的目标，你并不一定需要论证所有可再生能源都得到了广泛应用。只要证明部分可再生能源得到了广泛应用就足够了。你甚至可以呼吁加强对那些应用较少的可再生能源的开发。
Or, instead of arguing that every renewable source is or could be widely used, you might really want to be arguing that every (or most every?) place has at least some renewable source available to it, though there may be different sources in different places. This is a quite different and more subtle claim than the original, and gives your thinking some interesting room to move. (Might this argument have counterexamples too? I leave that question for you.)
或者，与其论证每一种可再生能源都已被或可能被广泛利用，你或许更想论证的是，每个（或几乎每个？）地方至少都有一些可再生能源可供利用，尽管不同地方的可再生能源种类可能有所不同。这与最初的论断截然不同，也更为微妙，为你的思考提供了更多有趣的空间。（这个论证是否也可能存在反例？这个问题留给你思考。）
Ask yourself about counterexamples when you are assessing others’ arguments as well as evaluating your own. Ask whether their conclusions might have to be revised and limited, or rethought in more subtle and complex directions. The same rules apply both to others’ arguments and to yours. The only difference is that you have a chance to correct your overgeneralizations yourself.
在评估他人论点以及评估自身论点时，都要思考是否存在反例。问问自己，他们的结论是否需要修正或限定，或者是否需要从更微妙、更复杂的角度重新思考。同样的原则适用于他人的论点，也适用于你自己的论点。唯一的区别在于，你有机会自行纠正过度概括的结论。
#↩
{19} III
{19} III
Arguments by Analogy 类比论证
There is an exception to Rule 7 (“Use more than one example”). Arguments by analogy, rather than multiplying examples to support a generalization, argue from one specific example to another, reasoning that because the two examples are alike in many ways, they are also alike in one further specific way.
规则7（“使用多个例子”）有一个例外。类比论证并非通过列举多个例子来支持概括，而是从一个具体例子推导出另一个具体例子，理由是这两个例子在许多方面相似，因此它们在某个特定方面也相似。
Valentina Tereshkova, Russian astronaut and first woman in space, famously quipped that
俄罗斯宇航员、首位进入太空的女性瓦伦蒂娜·捷列什科娃曾妙语连珠地说道：
If women can be railroad workers in Russia, why can’t they fly in space?
如果女性可以在俄罗斯当铁路工人，为什么她们不能飞上太空？
Russian women are as capable of demanding physical and technical work as men, Tereshkova is arguing, and as devoted to their work and their country—as proved by the example of female railroad workers. Therefore, women should also make fine astronauts. Spelled out, the argument looks like this:
捷列什科娃认为，俄罗斯女性和男性一样能够胜任高强度的体力劳动和技术工作，并且对工作和国家同样忠诚——铁路女工的例子就证明了这一点。因此，女性也应该能够成为优秀的宇航员。她的论点具体如下：
Women have proved themselves to be capable railroad workers in Russia.
在俄罗斯，女性已经证明自己是称职的铁路工人。
Being a railroad worker is like being an astronaut (because they both make extreme physical and technical demands).
当铁路工人就像当宇航员一样（因为他们都对体力和技术有极高的要求）。
Therefore, women can be capable astronauts as well.
因此，女性也可以成为合格的宇航员。
Notice the italicized word “like” in the second premise. When an argument stresses the likeness between two cases, it is very probably an argument from analogy.
注意第二个前提中斜体字“像”。当一个论证强调两个案例之间的相似性时，它很可能是一个类比论证。
{20}
12
Analogies require relevantly similar examples 类比需要相关相似的例子。
How do we evaluate arguments by analogy?
我们如何评价类比论证？
The first premise of an argument by analogy makes a claim about the example used as an analogy. Remember Rule 3: make sure this premise is true. Tereshkova’s argument could not even get off the ground, so to speak, if women had not proved themselves to be capable railroad workers in Russia.
类比论证的第一个前提是对用作类比的例子做出断言。记住规则3：确保这个前提为真。如果俄罗斯女性没有证明自己是称职的铁路工人，那么捷列什科娃的论证根本就无法成立。
The second premise in arguments by analogy claims that the example in the first premise is like the example about which the argument draws a conclusion. Evaluating this premise requires us to ask how relevantly similar the two cases are.
类比论证的第二个前提声称，第一个前提中的例子与该论证得出结论的例子相似。评估这个前提需要我们探究这两个例子在相关性上有多相似。
They do not have to be similar in every way. After all, being an astronaut is very different than working on the railroad. Trains don’t fly, for example—or when they do, the story does not have a happy ending. Astronauts better not wield sledgehammers. But argument by analogy only requires relevant similarities. Technical skill and physical strength and stamina seem to be Tereshkova’s real themes. Both astronauts and railroad workers require a lot of both.
它们不必在所有方面都相似。毕竟，当宇航员和在铁路工作截然不同。例如，火车不会飞——或者即使会飞，故事也不会有美好的结局。宇航员最好也别挥舞大锤。但类比论证只需要相关的相似之处。技术技能、体力和耐力似乎才是捷列什科娃真正想表达的主题。宇航员和铁路工人都需要大量的这两方面能力。
So how relevantly similar, in the end, is Tereshkova’s analogy? For modern astronauts, you might think that sheer physical stamina is less relevant than skill at running experiments and making scientific observations—skills not necessarily related to being a good railroad worker. In Tereshkova’s time, however, physical strength and stamina were much more important, as was body size: the early capsules were quite small and actually suited women’s physiques better. The other key factor was that the early Russian astronauts had to eject from their capsule and parachute to the ground at the end of their missions—and Tereshkova was a champion parachutist. This was probably the key factor, and is related to strength and stamina, though not to railroad work.
那么，特列什科娃的类比最终究竟有多大意义呢？对于现代宇航员来说，你可能会认为，相比于实验技能和科学观察能力，纯粹的体能远不如操作技能重要——而这些技能与成为一名优秀的铁路工人并无必然联系。然而，在特列什科娃的时代，体力和耐力却至关重要，体型也同样重要：早期的太空舱非常小，实际上更适合女性的体型。另一个关键因素是，早期的俄罗斯宇航员必须在任务结束后弹射出舱，借助降落伞安全返回地面——而特列什科娃是一位跳伞冠军。这或许才是关键所在，它与体力和耐力有关，尽管与铁路工作无关。
Tereshkova’s analogy partially succeeds, then, especially for her time, though it is less persuasive now. But of course, since there have now been many successful female astronauts, it is also less necessary.
特列什科娃的类比在某种程度上是成立的，尤其是在她所处的时代，尽管现在看来说服力有所下降。当然，由于现在已经有很多成功的女宇航员，这种类比的必要性也降低了。
{21} Here is a more challenging argument from analogy.
{21} 这里有一个更具挑战性的类比论证。
An interesting switch was pulled in Rome yesterday by Adam Nordwell, an American Chippewa chief. As he descended his plane from California dressed in full tribal regalia, Nordwell announced in the name of the American Indian people that he was taking possession of Italy “by right of discovery” in the same way that Christopher Columbus did in America. “I proclaim this day the day of the discovery of Italy,” said Nordwell. “What right did Columbus have to discover America when it had already been inhabited for thousands of years? The same right I now have to come to Italy and proclaim the discovery of your country.” 2
昨天，美国奇佩瓦族酋长亚当·诺德威尔在罗马上演了一出令人意想不到的戏码。他身着全套部落服饰，从加利福尼亚乘飞机抵达罗马，并以美国印第安人的名义宣布，他将以“发现权”的方式占领意大利，就像克里斯托弗·哥伦布发现美洲一样。“我宣布今天是意大利的发现日，”诺德威尔说道，“美洲早在几千年前就有人居住，哥伦布有什么权利去发现它？我现在也有同样的权利来到意大利，宣布发现你们的国家。”
Nordwell is suggesting that his “discovery” of Italy is like Columbus’s “discovery” of America in at least one important way: both Nordwell and Columbus claimed a country that already had been inhabited by its own people for centuries. Thus, Nordwell insists that he has as much “right” to claim Italy as Columbus had to claim America. But, of course, Nordwell has no right at all to claim Italy. It follows that Columbus had no right at all to claim America.
诺德威尔暗示，他对意大利的“发现”至少在一个重要方面与哥伦布对美洲的“发现”相似：诺德威尔和哥伦布都声称拥有一个早已有人居住数个世纪的国家的主权。因此，诺德威尔坚称，他拥有与哥伦布宣称拥有美洲主权同等的“权利”来宣称拥有意大利的主权。但显然，诺德威尔根本没有任何权利宣称拥有意大利的主权。由此可见，哥伦布也根本没有任何权利宣称拥有美洲的主权。
Nordwell has no right to claim Italy for another people, let alone “by right of discovery” (because Italy has been inhabited by its own people for centuries).
Nordwell 没有权利为其他民族宣称对意大利的主权，更不用说“通过发现权”了（因为意大利几个世纪以来一直由其本国人民居住）。
Columbus’s claim to America “by right of discovery” is like Nordwell’s claim to Italy (America, too, had been inhabited by its own people for centuries).
哥伦布“通过发现权”对美洲的主张，就像诺德威尔对意大利的主张一样（美洲也早已有自己的人民居住了几个世纪）。
Therefore, Columbus had no right to claim America for another people, let alone “by right of discovery.”
因此，哥伦布无权将美洲据为己有，更遑论“通过发现权”来宣称美洲是其他民族的领地。
How good is Nordwell’s analogy? Obviously, twentieth-century Italy is not just like fifteenth-century America. Italy is known to every twentieth-century schoolchild, whereas America was unknown to much of the world in the fifteenth century. Nordwell is not an explorer, and a commercial jet is not the Santa Maria. But are these differences relevant to Nordwell’s analogy? Nordwell simply means to remind us that it is senseless to claim a country already inhabited {22} by its own people. Whether that land is known to the world’s schoolchildren, or how the “discoverer” arrived there, is not important. The more appropriate reaction might have been to try to establish diplomatic relations, as we would try to do today if somehow the land and people of Italy had just been discovered. That’s Nordwell’s point, and, taken in that way, his analogy makes a good (and unsettling) argument.
诺德威尔的类比究竟如何？显然，二十世纪的意大利与十五世纪的美国截然不同。二十世纪的每个学童都熟知意大利，而十五世纪的美国对世界大部分地区来说却鲜为人知。诺德威尔并非探险家，商用喷气式飞机也并非圣玛利亚号。但这些差异与诺德威尔的类比相关吗？诺德威尔只是想提醒我们，声称拥有一个早已被其人民居住的国家是毫无意义的。{22} 这片土地是否为世人所知，或者“发现者”是如何到达那里的，都无关紧要。更恰当的做法或许是尝试建立外交关系，就像我们今天如果意大利的土地和人民刚刚被发现时会做的那样。这正是诺德威尔的观点，从这个角度来看，他的类比提出了一个有力（且令人不安）的论点。
__________________
2. Miami News , 23 September 1973.
2.《迈阿密新闻报》，1973 年 9 月 23 日。
#↩
{23} IV
{23} IV
Arguments from Authority 诉诸权威的论证
No one can be an expert through direct experience on everything there is to know. We do not live in ancient times ourselves and therefore cannot know first-hand at what age women tended to marry back then. Few of us have enough experience to judge which kinds of cars are safest in a crash. We do not know first-hand what is really happening in Sri Lanka or the state legislature, or even in the average American classroom or street corner. Instead, we must rely on others—better-situated people, organizations, surveys, or reference works—to tell us much of what we need to know about the world. We argue like this:
没有人能凭借亲身经历成为所有领域的专家。我们并非生活在古代，因此无法亲身了解当时女性的结婚年龄。我们当中很少有人拥有足够的经验来判断哪种汽车在碰撞事故中最安全。我们并不了解斯里兰卡或州议会，甚至美国普通教室或街角的真实情况。相反，我们必须依靠他人——那些处境更佳的人、组织、调查或参考资料——来了解我们所需的大部分世界信息。我们的论证方式如下：
X (a source that ought to know) says that Y.
X（一个应该知道内情的人）说Y。
Therefore, Y is true.
因此，Y 为真。
For instance:
例如：
Dr. Aubrey de Grey says that people can live to be 1,000 years old.
奥布里·德·格雷博士说，人可以活到1000岁。
Therefore, people can live to be 1,000 years old.
因此，人类可以活到1000岁。
It’s a risky business, though. Supposed experts may be overconfident (they’re human too), or may be misled, or may not even be reliable. And everyone has biases, after all, even if innocent ones. Once again we must consider a checklist of standards that truly authoritative sources need to meet.
但这并非易事。所谓的专家可能过于自信（毕竟他们也是人），可能被误导，甚至可能根本不可靠。而且，每个人都有偏见，即使是无辜的偏见。因此，我们必须再次审视真正权威的信息来源需要满足的一系列标准。
{24}
13
Cite your sources 请注明出处
Who’s got your back?
谁在你身后支持你？
Some factual assertions are so obvious or well known that they do not need support at all. It is usually not necessary to prove that the United States currently has fifty states or that Juliet loved Romeo. However, a precise figure for the current population of the United States, say, does need a citation. Likewise, to develop Valentina Tereshkova’s argument for sending women to space, we’d need to find knowledgeable authorities to establish that women were indeed capable railroad workers in Russia.
有些事实陈述显而易见或众所周知，根本不需要任何佐证。例如，我们通常无需证明美国目前有五十个州，或者朱丽叶爱着罗密欧。然而，例如，美国当前人口的确切数字则需要引用来源。同样，为了支持瓦伦蒂娜·捷列什科娃关于女性应被送上太空的论点，我们需要找到权威人士来证实俄罗斯女性确实能够胜任铁路工人的工作。
NO:
不：
I once read that there are cultures in which makeup and clothes are mostly men’s business, not women’s.
我曾经读到过，在某些文化中，化妆和服装主要是男人的事，而不是女人的事。
If you’re arguing about whether men and women everywhere follow the gender roles familiar to us, this is a relevant example—a striking case of different gender roles. But few of us know anything about this sort of difference first-hand, and it will probably seem surprising and even unlikely to many people. To nail down the argument, then, you need to call upon a fully cited source.
如果你正在讨论世界各地的男性和女性是否都遵循我们所熟知的性别角色，那么这就是一个相关的例子——一个性别角色差异显著的案例。但我们当中很少有人亲身经历过这种差异，而且对许多人来说，这或许会显得令人惊讶，甚至难以置信。因此，为了使论点站得住脚，你需要引用完整可靠的资料来源。
YES:
是的：
Carol Beckwith’s classic study of “Niger’s Wodaabe” ( National Geographic 164, no. 4 [October 1983], pp. 483–509) reports that among the West African Fulani peoples such as the Wodaabe, makeup and clothes are mostly men’s business.
卡罗尔·贝克威斯 (Carol Beckwith) 在其经典研究《尼日尔的沃达贝人》(National Geographic 164, no. 4 [1983 年 10 月], pp. 483–509) 中指出，在西非富拉尼人（如沃达贝人）中，化妆和服装大多是男人的事。
Citation styles vary—consult a handbook of style to find the appropriate format for your purposes—but all include the same basic information: enough so that others can easily find the source on their own.
引用格式各不相同——请查阅格式手册，找到适合您用途的格式——但所有引用格式都包含相同的基本信息：足以让其他人能够轻松地自行找到来源。
{25}
14
Seek informed sources 寻找知情人士
Who knows?
谁知道呢？
Sources must be qualified to make the statements they make. Honda mechanics are qualified to discuss the merits of different Hondas, midwives and obstetricians are qualified to discuss pregnancy and childbirth, teachers are qualified to discuss the state of their schools, and so on. These sources are qualified because they have the appropriate background and information. For the best information about global climate change, go to climatologists, not politicians.
信息来源必须具备相应的资质才能发表其言论。本田汽车技师有资格讨论不同本田车型的优劣，助产士和妇产科医生有资格讨论怀孕和分娩，教师有资格讨论学校的状况，等等。这些信息来源之所以合格，是因为他们拥有相应的背景知识和信息。想要了解全球气候变化的最佳信息，请咨询气候学家，而不是政客。
Where a source’s qualifications are not immediately clear, an argument must explain them. Dr. Aubrey de Grey says that people can live to be 1,000 years old? Well, who is this Aubrey de Grey to expect us to believe him about such things? Here is an answer: He is a gerontologist who has developed detailed theories of the causes of aging (it is not inevitable, he argues) and possible preventive interventions, which he has laid out in several detailed books such as The Mitochondrial Free Radical Theory of Aging (Cambridge University Press, 1999), for which he was awarded a PhD in biology by Cambridge University in 2000. When someone like that says that people can live to be 1,000 years old—unlikely as it seems—it is not a random or unprofessional opinion. We should give him a serious hearing.
如果信息来源的资质不明，论证就必须加以解释。奥布里·德·格雷博士说人可以活到1000岁？那么，这位奥布里·德·格雷究竟是谁，凭什么让我们相信他这种说法？答案是：他是一位老年学家，对衰老的原因（他认为衰老并非不可避免）和可能的预防干预措施进行了详细的理论研究，并在多部著作中阐述了这些理论，例如《线粒体自由基衰老理论》（剑桥大学出版社，1999年）。他凭借此书于2000年获得剑桥大学生物学博士学位。当像他这样的人说人可以活到1000岁时——尽管这听起来不太可能——这并非随意或不专业的观点。我们应该认真听取他的意见。
As you explain your source’s qualifications, you can also add more direct evidence to your argument.
在解释信息来源的资质时，你也可以为你的论点添加更多直接证据。
Carol Beckwith’s classic study of “Niger’s Wodaabe” ( National Geographic 164, no. 4 [October 1983], pp. 483–509) reports that among the West African Fulani peoples such as the Wodaabe, makeup and clothes are mostly men’s business. Beckwith and an anthropologist colleague lived with the Wodaabe for two years and observed many dances for which the men prepared by lengthy preening, face-painting, and teeth-whitening. (Her article includes many pictures too.) Wodaabe women watch, comment, and choose mates for their beauty—which the men say is the natural way. “Our beauty makes the women want us,” one says.
卡罗尔·贝克威斯在其经典著作《尼日尔的沃达贝人》（《国家地理》第164卷第4期[1983年10月]，第483-509页）中指出，在沃达贝人等西非富拉尼族群中，化妆和服饰主要由男性负责。贝克威斯和一位人类学家同事与沃达贝人共同生活了两年，观察了许多男性为舞蹈做准备的场景，包括长时间的梳妆打扮、脸部彩绘和牙齿美白。（她的文章中也包含许多图片。）沃达贝女性则观看、评论并以美貌为择偶标准——男性认为这是自然之道。“我们的美貌让女性爱上我们，”一位男性说道。
{26} Note that an informed source need not fit our general stereotype of an “authority”—and a person who fits our stereotype of an authority may not even be an informed source. If you’re checking out colleges, for instance, students are the best authorities, not administrators or recruiters, because it’s the students who know what student life is really like. (Just be sure to find yourself a representative sample.)
{26} 请注意，知情人士未必符合我们对“权威”的普遍刻板印象——而符合我们刻板印象的权威人士甚至可能并非知情人士。例如，如果您正在了解大学，学生才是最佳的权威，而不是行政人员或招生人员，因为只有学生才真正了解大学生活。（但务必确保找到具有代表性的样本。）
Note also that experts on one subject are not necessarily informed about every subject on which they offer opinions.
还要注意的是，某一领域的专家未必对他们发表意见的每个领域都了如指掌。
Beyoncé is a vegan. Therefore, veganism is the best diet.
碧昂丝是素食主义者。因此，素食主义是最好的饮食方式。
Beyoncé may be a fabulous entertainer, but a diet expert she’s not. (Also, it is not entirely clear that she is a vegan, apparently.) Likewise, just because someone can put the title “Doctor” before their name—that is, just because they have a PhD or MD in some field—does not mean that they are qualified to deliver opinions on any subject whatsoever.
碧昂丝或许是一位才华横溢的艺人，但她绝非营养专家。（而且，她是否是素食主义者也尚不完全清楚。）同样，仅仅因为某人可以在名字前加上“博士”头衔——也就是说，仅仅因为他们拥有某个领域的博士学位——并不意味着他们就有资格对任何话题发表意见。
Sometimes we must rely on sources whose knowledge is better than ours but still limited in various ways. On occasion, the best information we can get about what is happening in a war zone or a political trial or inside a business or bureaucracy is fragmentary and filtered through journalists, international human rights organizations, corporate watchdogs, and so on. If you must rely on a source that may have limited knowledge in this way, acknowledge the problem. Let your readers or hearers decide whether imperfect authority is better than none at all.
有时我们不得不依赖一些信息来源，他们的知识虽然比我们更丰富，但在各个方面仍然存在局限性。例如，我们有时能获取到的关于战区、政治审判、企业或官僚机构内部情况的最佳信息，往往是零散的，并且经过记者、国际人权组织、企业监督机构等渠道的过滤。如果你必须依赖这类信息来源，请坦诚面对这个问题。让你的读者或听众来判断，不完善的信息来源是否比没有信息来源更好。
Truly informed sources rarely expect others to accept their conclusions simply because they assert them. Good sources will offer at least some reasons or evidence—examples, facts, analogies, other kinds of arguments—to help explain and defend their conclusions. Beckwith, for example, offers photographs and stories from the years she lived with the Wodaabe. Thus, while we might need to take some of their specific claims on authority alone (for instance, we must take Beckwith at her word that she had certain experiences), we can expect even the best sources to offer arguments as well as their own judgments in support of their general conclusions. Look for those arguments, then, and look at them critically as well.
真正了解情况的信息来源很少会期望别人仅仅因为他们提出了自己的结论就接受它。好的信息来源至少会提供一些理由或证据——例如例子、事实、类比或其他论证方式——来帮助解释和捍卫他们的结论。例如，贝克威斯就提供了她与沃达贝人共同生活期间的照片和故事。因此，虽然我们可能需要仅凭权威性来采信他们的一些具体说法（例如，我们必须相信贝克威斯关于她有某些经历的说法），但我们可以预期，即使是最好的信息来源也会提供论证以及他们自身的判断来支持他们的总体结论。因此，请寻找这些论证，并对其进行批判性审视。
{27}
15
Seek impartial sources 寻找公正的信息来源
People who have the most at stake in a dispute are usually not the best sources of information about the issues involved. Sometimes they may not even tell the truth. People accused in criminal trials are presumed innocent until proven guilty, but we seldom completely believe their claims of innocence without confirmation from impartial witnesses.
在纠纷中利益攸关的人通常并非了解相关问题的最佳信息来源。有时，他们甚至可能说谎。刑事审判中，被告在被证明有罪之前都推定为无罪，但如果没有公正证人的证实，我们很少会完全相信他们的清白之词。
Readiness to tell the truth as one sees it, though, is not always enough. The truth as one honestly sees it can still be biased. We tend to see what we expect to see. We notice, remember, and pass on information that supports our point of view, but we may not be quite so motivated when the evidence points the other way.
然而，即便愿意如实陈述所见所闻，也并非总是足够。即使是诚实地看待的真相，也可能带有偏见。我们往往倾向于看到自己期望看到的东西。我们会注意到、记住并传播那些支持我们观点的信息，但当证据指向相反的方向时，我们可能就不会那么积极地去关注了。
Therefore, look for impartial sources: people or organizations who do not have a stake in the immediate issue, and who have a prior and primary interest in accuracy, such as (some) university scientists or statistical databases. Don’t just rely on politicians or interest groups on one side of a major public question for the most accurate information about the issues at stake. Don’t just rely on manufacturers’ advertisements for reliable information concerning their products.
因此，要寻找公正的信息来源：那些与当前问题没有直接利益关系，且首先关注信息准确性的个人或组织，例如（一些）大学科学家或统计数据库。不要仅仅依赖政客或某一方的利益集团来获取关于重大公共问题的最准确信息。同样，也不要仅仅依赖制造商的广告来获取关于其产品的可靠信息。
NO:
不：
My car dealer recommends that I pay $300 to rustproof my car. He should know; I guess I’d better do it.
我的汽车经销商建议我花300美元做汽车防锈处理。他应该知道，我想我最好还是去做。
He probably does know, but he might not be entirely reliable, either. The best information about consumer products and services comes from independent consumer testing agencies, agencies not affiliated with any manufacturer or provider but answering to consumers who want the most accurate information they can get. Do some research!
他可能知道，但他的话也未必完全可靠。关于消费产品和服务，最权威的信息来自独立的消费者测试机构，这些机构不隶属于任何制造商或供应商，而是为那些希望获得最准确信息的消费者服务。不妨做些调查！
YES:
是的：
Experts at Consumer Reports say that rust problems have almost vanished in modern cars due to better manufacturing, {28} and advise that rustproofing is not needed ( Consumer Reports, “Watch Out for These Car Sales Tricks,” http://www.consumerreports.org/buying-a-car/car-sales-tricks/ , 2 February 2017; and Sami Haaj-Assaad, “Should You Rust Proof Your New Car?” Auto-Guide.com , 21 March 2013).
《消费者报告》的专家表示，由于制造工艺的改进，现代汽车的生锈问题几乎已经消失，{28}并建议无需进行防锈处理（《消费者报告》，“小心这些汽车销售伎俩”，http://www.consumerreports.org/buying-a-car/car-sales-tricks/，2017 年 2 月 2 日；以及 Sami Haaj-Assaad，“新车需要防锈吗？”Auto-Guide.com，2013 年 3 月 21 日）。
On political matters, especially when the disagreements are basically over statistics, look to independent government agencies, such as the Census Bureau, or to university studies or other independent sources. Organizations like Doctors Without Borders are relatively impartial sources on the human rights situation in other countries because they practice medicine, not politics: they are not trying to support or oppose any specific government.
在政治问题上，尤其是在分歧主要集中在统计数据上时，应参考独立的政府机构，例如人口普查局，或者大学研究或其他独立来源。像无国界医生这样的组织，在了解其他国家的人权状况方面相对公正，因为他们从事的是医疗工作，而非政治活动：他们既不支持也不反对任何特定政府。
Of course, independence and impartiality are not always easy to judge, either. Be sure that your sources are genuinely independent and not just interest groups masquerading under an independent-sounding name. Check who funds them; check their other publications; look for their track record; watch the tone of their statements. Sources that make extreme or simplistic claims, or spend most of their time attacking and demeaning the other side, weaken their own claims. Again, seek out sources that offer constructive arguments and responsibly acknowledge and thoroughly engage the arguments and evidence on the other side. At the very least, try to confirm for yourself any factual claim quoted from a potentially biased source. Good arguments cite their sources (Rule 13); look them up. Make sure the evidence is quoted correctly and not pulled out of context, and check for further information that might be helpful.
当然，独立性和公正性也并非总是易于判断。务必确保你的信息来源真正独立，而不是披着独立外衣的利益集团。查明他们的资金来源；查看他们的其他出版物；了解他们的过往记录；注意他们的言论语气。那些提出极端或简单化论断，或将大部分时间用于攻击和贬低对方的信息来源，会削弱自身的论点。再次强调，寻找那些提供建设性论证，并负责任地承认和全面回应对方论点和证据的信息来源。至少，对于任何可能带有偏见的信息来源所引用的事实，都要尝试自行核实。好的论证会引用来源（规则13）；查阅这些来源。确保证据引用正确，没有断章取义，并查找可能有所帮助的其他信息。
16
Cross-check sources 交叉核对来源
Don’t bet on a one-off
不要指望一次性事件。
Consult and compare a variety of sources to see if other, equally good authorities agree. Are the experts sharply divided or in agreement? If they’re pretty much in agreement, theirs is the safe view to take—and the opposite view is, at the very least, unwise, however strongly it may appeal to us. Authoritative views can certainly be wrong at times. But non authoritative views are regularly wrong.
查阅并比较各种来源，看看其他同样权威的专家是否也持相同观点。专家们的意见是截然相反还是基本一致？如果他们的观点基本一致，那么他们的观点就是最稳妥的——而相反的观点，无论多么吸引我们，至少都是不明智的。权威的观点当然也会犯错，但非权威的观点却经常出错。
{29} On the other hand, cross-checking may sometimes reveal that the experts themselves disagree on some subject. In that case, reserve judgment yourself. Don’t jump in with two feet where truly informed people tread with care. Better to argue on some other grounds—or rethink your conclusions.
{29} 另一方面，交叉核查有时会发现专家们自己在某些问题上也存在分歧。在这种情况下，最好不要妄下结论。不要贸然行事，尤其是在真正了解情况的人都会谨慎行事的地方。最好从其他方面进行论证，或者重新思考你的结论。
What about our friend Aubrey de Grey, then, and our hopes of living 1,000 years? Alas, when you start to cross-check, it turns out that de Grey’s work is widely regarded as well-developed and his research as certainly worth pursuing, but very few other experts are persuaded. 3 Many are sharply critical. He’s an outlier. Living vastly longer may be an appealing thought, but don’t count it very likely.
那么，我们的朋友奥布里·德·格雷（Aubrey de Grey）和我们活到1000岁的希望又该如何解释呢？唉，当你开始核实时，你会发现，德·格雷的研究成果被广泛认为是成熟的，他的研究也确实值得继续，但其他专家却鲜少认同。许多人对他持尖锐的批评态度。他是个特例。活得更久或许是个诱人的想法，但不要指望它真的会发生。
On most significant topics you can probably find some disagreement if you look hard enough. Worse, on some topics the appearance of controversy may be created even when there is virtually no disagreement among qualified authorities. Although there was a time when experts disagreed about global climate change, for example, the world scientific community is now nearly unanimous that the climate is changing and that human activity has something to do with it. Sure, there’s still loud disagreement in some media and election campaigns, but virtually none among trained climate scientists looking at the data as objectively as they can. There are also a few reasoned critiques of the climate-change consensus, but in the best judgment of almost everyone actually in the field, they do not change the bottom line. Some of the critiques have even sharpened the science, but the critics, even when qualified, are (very markedly) outliers.
在大多数重要议题上，只要你仔细寻找，总能发现一些分歧。更糟糕的是，在某些议题上，即使权威专家之间几乎没有分歧，也会人为制造争议的假象。例如，虽然专家们曾经对全球气候变化存在分歧，但如今世界科学界几乎一致认为气候正在变化，而且人类活动与此密切相关。当然，在一些媒体和竞选活动中仍然存在激烈的争论，但在训练有素、尽可能客观地审视数据的气候科学家中，几乎没有分歧。也有一些对气候变化共识的理性批评，但几乎所有业内人士都认为，这些批评并不能改变最终结论。有些批评甚至提升了科学的严谨性，但这些批评者，即便具备一定的权威性，也明显属于少数派。
Ideology seems to be the driving force here—not actual evidence or professional judgment. You may need to look into seeming controversies like these to see how seriously to take them. 4
意识形态似乎是这里的驱动力——而非实际证据或专业判断。你可能需要深入调查这类看似有争议的事件，才能判断其严重程度。4
{30}
17
Build your Internet savvy 提升你的互联网技能
Online, even the most baseless or hateful opinion site can dress itself up to look plausible and even professional. Academic book publishers and even most public libraries have at least some checks on the reliability and tone of the books and other materials they collect, but on the Internet, it is still the Wild West—no checks. You’re on your own.
在网络上，即使是最毫无根据或充满仇恨的评论网站也能伪装得看似可信，甚至专业。学术出版社，甚至大多数公共图书馆，至少都会对所收藏书籍和其他资料的可靠性和语气进行一些审核，但在互联网上，它仍然是一片蛮荒之地——没有任何审核机制。你只能靠自己。
“The Internet” by itself, in any case, is not any kind of authority. It merely transmits other sources. Savvy users know how to evaluate those sources—they apply the rules in this book. Rule 13, for example: What is the source? With many websites this may be difficult to tell—and that’s a red flag right there. Are the sources well-informed (Rule 14)? Reliable (15)? Or are the sites pushing an agenda—trying to sell you something, or to manipulate your view on some issues by, say, using loaded language (5), unrepresentative data (8), or outlying or phony “experts” (14 and 16)? At minimum, cross-check other, independent websites on the same issue (16).
无论如何，“互联网”本身并非权威。它只是其他信息来源的载体。精明的用户知道如何评估这些信息来源——他们会运用本书中的规则。例如，规则13：信息来源是什么？很多网站的信息来源难以辨别——而这本身就是一个危险信号。这些信息来源是否信息翔实（规则14）？是否可靠（规则15）？或者这些网站是否带有某种目的——试图向你推销产品，或者通过使用带有倾向性的语言（规则5）、不具代表性的数据（规则8）或虚假的“专家”（规则14和16）来操纵你对某些问题的看法？至少，你应该就同一问题交叉核对其他独立网站（规则16）。
Savvy users also dig deeper than the standard Web search. Search engines cannot search “everything”—far from it. In fact, the most reliable and detailed information on any given topic is often found in databases or other academic resources that standard search engines cannot enter at all. You may need a password; ask your teacher or librarian.
精明的用户还会进行比普通网络搜索更深入的挖掘。搜索引擎不可能搜索到“所有内容”——远非如此。事实上，任何特定主题最可靠、最详细的信息往往存在于数据库或其他学术资源中，而这些资源是普通搜索引擎根本无法访问的。您可能需要密码；请咨询您的老师或图书管理员。
Savvy users may also—cautiously!—consult Wikipedia. It’s certainly true that “anyone can edit Wikipedia,” as is often objected, and as a result false and defamatory information has sometimes been posted. Subtle biases surely persist. Still, Wikipedia’s very openness {31} can also be an advantage. Every article is subject to constant scrutiny and correction by other users. Many users are moved to contribute additional information or improvements too. Over time, many articles tend to become more comprehensive and neutral. Wikipedian editors sometimes intervene if there is too much contention, and some hot-topic articles are not open to general editing, but the end result is that Wikipedia’s error rate (remember Rule 9!) has been compared favorably even to the Encyclopedia Britannica . 5
精明的用户也可以——但务必谨慎！——查阅维基百科。诚然，“任何人都可以编辑维基百科”，这一点常被质疑，因此也确实出现了虚假和诽谤性的信息。微妙的偏见也确实存在。然而，维基百科的开放性{31}本身也是一种优势。每篇文章都会受到其他用户的持续审查和修正。许多用户也会因此贡献补充信息或进行改进。随着时间的推移，许多文章往往会变得更加全面和中立。如果争议过多，维基百科编辑有时会进行干预，一些热门话题的文章也不对公众开放编辑，但最终的结果是，维基百科的错误率（请记住规则9！）甚至可以与《不列颠百科全书》相媲美。5
Of course, savvy encyclopedia users know that they cannot simply cite Wikipedia (or, usually, any other encyclopedia) to back up their claims. Wikipedia’s intention is to organize and summarize knowledge on a subject, and then to point readers to the real sources. Savvy users also remain watchful—as in any source—for subtle hints of loaded language, dismissive accounts of disfavored views, and the like.
当然，精明的百科全书用户都知道，他们不能简单地引用维基百科（或者通常情况下，任何其他百科全书）来佐证自己的观点。维基百科的目的是整理和总结某一主题的知识，然后引导读者找到真正的来源。精明的用户也会像对待任何其他信息来源一样，时刻警惕那些带有倾向性的语言、对不受欢迎观点的轻蔑描述等等。
Every reference source is a product of a group of people with their limits and biases, acknowledged and unacknowledged. At least as important as avoiding mistakes or bias is having a means of correcting them—and fast—and at that Wikipedia is unexcelled. Random insertions and vandalism are typically repaired within minutes, and every change is tracked and explained (check out every page’s “View History” tab) and sometimes widely debated as well (check out the “Talk” tabs). What other reference source is so transparent and self-correcting? Really savvy users might join the work of making Wikipedia still better!
任何参考资料都是一群人共同努力的成果，他们难免存在局限性和偏见，无论这些局限和偏见是公开的还是隐晦的。避免错误或偏见固然重要，但拥有快速纠正错误和偏见的机制也同样重要——而维基百科在这方面堪称翘楚。随意插入的内容和恶意破坏通常会在几分钟内得到修复，每一次更改都会被追踪和解释（请查看每个页面的“查看历史”标签），有时还会引发广泛的讨论（请查看“讨论”标签）。还有哪个参考资料如此透明且具有自我纠正能力呢？真正精通的用户或许会加入到维基百科的改进工作中来！

Of course, once again, the consensus of experts may be wrong. Still, expert agreement is usually the best we can do. Even climate change “deniers” would not, say, go against the unanimous advice of their doctors if they were to learn that they might be seriously ill. They would not, so to say, bet their life that all their doctors are wrong, no matter how fervently they might wish it. But they would have us bet the future of Earth itself that the consensus of climate experts is wrong? Current efforts on the part of some politicians to shut down climate research, and even to prevent scientists from communicating with the public or public agencies from planning for climate-change adaptation, are even worse: they reveal not a constructive and evidence-based skepticism, but (it seems) just the opposite. Even responsible denial needs evidence!

Thomas Farmer的简明教科书《现代气候变化科学》（Springer出版社，2015年）入手。当然，专家共识也可能出错。然而，专家一致意见通常是我们所能达到的最佳结果。即使是气候变化“否认者”，如果得知自己可能身患重病，也不会违背医生的一致建议。他们不会拿自己的生命去赌所有医生的判断都是错的，无论他们多么希望如此。但他们却要我们拿地球的未来去赌气候专家的共识是错的？一些政客目前试图叫停气候研究，甚至阻止科学家与公众沟通，或阻止公共机构制定气候变化适应计划，这种做法更加糟糕：这并非出于建设性的、基于证据的怀疑，而是（似乎）恰恰相反。即使是负责任的否认也需要证据！
5. See Jim Giles, “Internet Encyclopedias Go Head to Head,” Nature 438 (7070): 900–1, December 2005. The March 2006 issue of Nature includes a response from Encyclopedia Britannica and a rejoinder from Nature .
